lastIndexOf.name: lastIndexOf
lastIndexOf.comment: Returns the last index in the list a of the given angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.element, starting the search at index angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.startIndex to 0. Returns -1 if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.element is not found.

length=.name: length=
length=.comment:
Changes the length of this list.

If angular/angular-mock.ListBase.length=.newLength is greater than the current length, entries are initialized to null.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if the list is fixed-length.

first.name: first
first.comment:
Returns the first element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError. Otherwise this method is equivalent to this.elementAt(0)

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides angular/angular-mock.ListBase.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one element in this collection.

iterator.name: iterator
iterator.comment: Returns an Iterator that iterates over this Iterable object.

last.name: last
last.comment:
Returns the last element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError.

length.name: length
length.comment:
Returns the number of objects in this list.

The valid indices for a list are 0 through length - 1.

reversed.name: reversed
reversed.comment: Returns an dart-core.Iterable of the objects in this list in reverse order.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

single.name: single
single.comment:
Returns the single element in this.

If this is empty or has more than one element throws a dart-core.StateError.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and angular/angular-mock.ListBase.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

[].comment: Returns the object at the given angular/angular-mock.ListBase.[].index in the list or throws a dart-core.RangeError if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.[].index is out of bounds.

[]=.comment: Sets the value at the given angular/angular-mock.ListBase.[]=.index in the list to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.[]=.value or throws a dart-core.RangeError if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.[]=.index is out of bounds.

add.name: add
add.comment:
Adds value to the end of this list, extending the length by one.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if the list is fixed-length.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Appends all objects of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.addAll.iterable to the end of this list.

Extends the length of the list by the number of objects in angular/angular-mock.ListBase.addAll.iterable. Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this list is fixed-length.

any.name: any
any.comment: Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the predicate angular/angular-mock.ListBase.any.test. Returns false otherwise.

asMap.name: asMap
asMap.comment:
Returns an unmodifiable dart-core.Map view of this.

The map uses the indices of this list as keys and the corresponding objects as values. The Map.keys dart-core.Iterable iterates the indices of this list in numerical order.

List<String> words = ['fee', 'fi', 'fo', 'fum'];
Map<int, String> map = words.asMap();
map[0] + map[1];   // 'feefi';
map.keys.toList(); // [0, 1, 2, 3]

clear.name: clear
clear.comment:
Removes all objects from this list; the length of the list becomes zero.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError, and retains all objects, if this is a fixed-length list.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment: Returns true if the collection contains an element equal to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.contains.element.

elementAt.name: elementAt
elementAt.comment:
Returns the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.elementAt.indexth element.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.elementAt.index must be non-negative and less than length.

Note: if this does not have a deterministic iteration order then the function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are at least angular/angular-mock.ListBase.elementAt.index elements in this.

every.name: every
every.comment: Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the predicate angular/angular-mock.ListBase.every.test. Returns false otherwise.

expand.name: expand
expand.comment:
Expands each element of this dart-core.Iterable into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable runs through the elements returned by angular/angular-mock.ListBase.expand.f for each element of this, in order.

The returned dart-core.Iterable is lazy, and calls angular/angular-mock.ListBase.expand.f for each element of this every time it's iterated.

fillRange.name: fillRange
fillRange.comment:
Sets the objects in the range angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fillRange.start inclusive to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fillRange.end exclusive to the given fillValue.

An error occurs if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fillRange.start..angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fillRange.end is not a valid range for this.

firstWhere.name: firstWhere
firstWhere.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate angular/angular-mock.ListBase.firstWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.firstWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when angular/angular-mock.ListBase.firstWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

fold.name: fold
fold.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each element of the collection with an existing value using the provided function.

Use angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fold.initialValue as the initial value, and the function angular/angular-mock.ListBase.fold.combine to create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.fold(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment: Applies the function f to each element of this collection.

getRange.name: getRange
getRange.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable that iterates over the objects in the range angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.start inclusive to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.end exclusive.

An error occurs if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.end is before angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.start.

An error occurs if the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.start and angular/angular-mock.ListBase.getRange.end are not valid ranges at the time of the call to this method. The returned dart-core.Iterable behaves like skip(start).take(end - start). That is, it does not throw exceptions if this changes size.

List<String> colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink'];
Iterable<String> range = colors.getRange(1, 4);
range.join(', ');  // 'green, blue, orange'
colors.length = 3;
range.join(', ');  // 'green, blue'

indexOf.name: indexOf
indexOf.comment:
Returns the first index of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.indexOf.element in this list.

Searches the list from index start to the end of the list. The first time an object o is encountered so that o == element, the index of o is returned.

List<String> notes = ['do', 're', 'mi', 're'];
notes.indexOf('re');    // 1
notes.indexOf('re', 2); // 3

Returns -1 if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.indexOf.element is not found.

notes.indexOf('fa');    // -1

insert.name: insert
insert.comment:
Inserts the object at position angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insert.index in this list.

This increases the length of the list by one and shifts all objects at or after the index towards the end of the list.

An error occurs if the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insert.index is less than 0 or greater than length. An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

insertAll.name: insertAll
insertAll.comment:
Inserts all objects of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insertAll.iterable at position angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insertAll.index in this list.

This increases the length of the list by the length of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insertAll.iterable and shifts all later objects towards the end of the list.

An error occurs if the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.insertAll.index is less than 0 or greater than length. An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

join.name: join
join.comment:
Converts each element to a dart-core.String and concatenates the strings.

Converts each element to a dart-core.String by calling angular/angular-mock.ListBase.toString on it. Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.join.separator string.

lastIndexOf.name: lastIndexOf
lastIndexOf.comment: Returns the last index in the list a of the given angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.element, starting the search at index angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.startIndex to 0. Returns -1 if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastIndexOf.element is not found.

lastWhere.name: lastWhere
lastWhere.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when angular/angular-mock.ListBase.lastWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

map.name: map
map.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable where each element e of this is replaced by the result of f(e).

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function angular/angular-mock.ListBase.map.f will not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating multiple times over the the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function angular/angular-mock.ListBase.map.f multiple times on the same element.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
angular/angular-mock.ListBase.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If angular/angular-mock.ListBase.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

reduce.name: reduce
reduce.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining elements of the collection using the provided function.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.reduce((value, element) => value + element);

remove.name: remove
remove.comment:
Removes the first occurence of value from this list.

Returns true if value was in the list, false otherwise.

List<String> parts = ['head', 'shoulders', 'knees', 'toes'];
parts.remove('head'); // true
parts.join(', ');     // 'shoulders, knees, toes'

The method has no effect if value was not in the list.

// Note: 'head' has already been removed.
parts.remove('head'); // false
parts.join(', ');     // 'shoulders, knees, toes'

An dart-core.UnsupportedError occurs if the list is fixed-length.

removeAt.name: removeAt
removeAt.comment:
Removes the object at position angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeAt.index from this list.

This method reduces the length of this by one and moves all later objects down by one position.

Returns the removed object.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeAt.index must be in the range 0 index < length.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list. In that case the list is not modified.

removeLast.name: removeLast
removeLast.comment:
Pops and returns the last object in this list.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

removeRange.name: removeRange
removeRange.comment:
Removes the objects in the range angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeRange.start inclusive to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeRange.end exclusive.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeRange.start and angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeRange.end indices must be in the range 0 index length, and start end.

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list. In that case the list is not modified.

removeWhere.name: removeWhere
removeWhere.comment:
Removes all objects from this list that satisfy angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeWhere.test.

An object o satisfies angular/angular-mock.ListBase.removeWhere.test if test(o) is true.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
numbers.removeWhere((item) => item.length == 3);
numbers.join(', '); // 'three, four'

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

replaceRange.name: replaceRange
replaceRange.comment:
Removes the objects in the range angular/angular-mock.ListBase.replaceRange.start inclusive to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.replaceRange.end exclusive and inserts the contents of replacement in its place.

List<int> list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
list.replaceRange(1, 4, [6, 7]);
list.join(', '); // '1, 6, 7, 5'

An error occurs if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.replaceRange.start..angular/angular-mock.ListBase.replaceRange.end is not a valid range for this.

retainWhere.name: retainWhere
retainWhere.comment:
Removes all objects from this list that fail to satisfy angular/angular-mock.ListBase.retainWhere.test.

An object o satisfies angular/angular-mock.ListBase.retainWhere.test if test(o) is true.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
numbers.retainWhere((item) => item.length == 3);
numbers.join(', '); // 'one, two'

Throws an dart-core.UnsupportedError if this is a fixed-length list.

setAll.name: setAll
setAll.comment:
Overwrites objects of this with the objects of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setAll.iterable, starting at position angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setAll.index in this list.

List<String> list = ['a', 'b', 'c'];
list.setAll(1, ['bee', 'sea']);
list.join(', '); // 'a, bee, sea'

This operation does not increase the length of this.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setAll.index must be non-negative and no greater than length.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setAll.iterable must not have more elements than what can fit from angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setAll.index to length.

If iterable is based on this list, its values may change /during/ the setAll operation.

setRange.name: setRange
setRange.comment:
Copies the objects of angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.iterable, skipping angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.skipCount objects first, into the range angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.start, inclusive, to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.end, exclusive, of the list.

List<int> list1 = [1, 2, 3, 4];
List<int> list2 = [5, 6, 7, 8, 9];
// Copies the 4th and 5th items in list2 as the 2nd and 3rd items
// of list1.
list1.setRange(1, 3, list2, 3);
list1.join(', '); // '1, 8, 9, 4'

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.start and angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.end indices must satisfy 0 start end length. If angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.start equals angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.end, this method has no effect.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.iterable must have enough objects to fill the range from start to end after skipping angular/angular-mock.ListBase.setRange.skipCount objects.

If iterable is this list, the operation will copy the elements originally in the range from skipCount to skipCount + (end - start) to the range start to end, even if the two ranges overlap.

If iterable depends on this list in some other way, no guarantees are made.

shuffle.name: shuffle
shuffle.comment: Shuffles the elements of this list randomly.

singleWhere.name: singleWhere
singleWhere.comment: Returns the single element that satisfies angular/angular-mock.ListBase.singleWhere.test. If no or more than one element match then a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

skip.name: skip
skip.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips the first n elements.

If this has fewer than n elements, then the resulting Iterable is empty.

It is an error if n is negative.

skipWhile.name: skipWhile
skipWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips elements while angular/angular-mock.ListBase.skipWhile.test is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable iterates over all elements of this.

As long as the iterator's elements satisfy angular/angular-mock.ListBase.skipWhile.test they are discarded. Once an element does not satisfy the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.skipWhile.test the iterator stops testing and uses every later element unconditionally. That is, the elements of the returned Iterable are the elements of this starting from the first element that does not satisfy angular/angular-mock.ListBase.skipWhile.test.

sort.name: sort
sort.comment:
Sorts this list according to the order specified by the angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sort.compare function.

The angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sort.compare function must act as a dart-core.Comparator.

List<String> numbers = ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four'];
// Sort from shortest to longest.
numbers.sort((x, y) => x.length.compareTo(y.length));
numbers.join(', '); // 'one, two, four, three'

The default List implementations use angular/dart-core.Comparable.compare if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sort.compare is omitted.

List<int> nums = [13, 2, -11];
nums.sort();
     nums.join(', '); // '-11, 2, 13'

sublist.name: sublist
sublist.comment:
Returns a new list containing the objects from angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sublist.start inclusive to angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sublist.end exclusive.

List<String> colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink'];
colors.sublist(1, 3); // ['green', 'blue']

If angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sublist.end is omitted, the length of this is used.

colors.sublist(1);  // ['green', 'blue', 'orange', 'pink']

An error occurs if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sublist.start is outside the range 0 .. length or if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.sublist.end is outside the range start .. length.

take.name: take
take.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable with at most n elements.

The returned dart-core.Iterable may contain fewer than n elements, if this contains fewer than n elements.

It is an error if n is negative.

takeWhile.name: takeWhile
takeWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that stops once angular/angular-mock.ListBase.takeWhile.test is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable starts iterating over the elements of this.

When the iterator encounters an element e that does not satisfy angular/angular-mock.ListBase.takeWhile.test, it discards e and moves into the finished state. That is, it does not get or provide any more elements.

toList.name: toList
toList.comment:
Creates a dart-core.List containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

The elements are in iteration order. The list is fixed-length if angular/angular-mock.ListBase.toList.growable is false.

toSet.name: toSet
toSet.comment: Creates a dart-core.Set containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

where.name: where
where.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable with all elements that satisfy the predicate angular/angular-mock.ListBase.where.test.

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function angular/angular-mock.ListBase.where.test will not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating multiple times over the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function angular/angular-mock.ListBase.where.test multiple times on the same element.
